The paper discusses the effects of consensus and preference aggregation on the consistency of pairwise comparisons in group decisions, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and social computing (cs.SI). The analysis involves defining boundary properties and investigating the relation between inconsistency indices, which can be seen as a data science (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG) problem. Finally, the paper offers a reflection on the interpretation of the inconsistency of group preferences, which can be relevant to computational complexity (cs.CC) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
